{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UXVMK8piKgwtqJcwozYEQt","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture:\n\n1. **Cluster settings**: Both persistent and transient are empty `{}` — no non-default cluster settings.\n\n2. **Index settings** for `audit-index`:\n   - `number_of_shards`: 3 (default is 1)\n   - `number_of_replicas`: 1 (default is 1, so this is actually default)\n   - `routing.allocation.require.tier`: \"hot\" (non-default — this is a custom routing requirement)\n   - `routing.allocation.include._tier_preference`: \"data_content\" (default ES behavior but could have been explicitly set)\n3. **ILM policies**: All the policies I'm seeing are built-in Elasticsearch ones with `\"managed\": true` — the `180-days-default`, `30-days-default`, `365-days-default`, `7-days-default`, and `90-days-default` are all standard policies, so there are no custom ILM policies to roll back.\n\n4. **Node attributes**: The `tier: hot` attribute is set across all nodes as the non-default setting, while the other attributes like `xpack.installed`, `transform.config_version`, and `ml.config_version` are automatically managed by Elasticsearch.\n\nFor the `audit-index` specifically, I need to remove the `index.routing.allocation.require.tier = \"hot\"` setting, though the shard count can't be changed on an existing open index. Looking more closely at the tier preference setting, it appears Elasticsearch automatically assigns `_tier_preference` for indices managed by ILM, so I need to determine whether that's actually a non-default configuration or just the expected behavior.\n\n, node attributes are set in the Elasticsearch configuration rather than through the API since they're static. I should check the StatefulSet config to see how these are configured, and also look for any existing `rollback-rehearsal` ConfigMap. Looking at the index settings more carefully, `routing.allocation.include._tier_preference: data_content` is actually the default behavior in ES 8.x, so the main non-default settings are the shard count and the explicit tier routing requirement. The non-default settings boil down to three things: the shard count on `audit-index` which can't be changed, the tier routing requirement which can be removed, and the node attributes set in the configuration which would require a restart to revert. Let me check how the StatefulSet configures those node attributes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4090,"cache_read_input_tokens":30323,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4090},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8a5b4a78-ed46-4e06-8aac-06a06e5ca78c","uuid":"60db4757-46fb-4c98-8bfd-c1a467b49b35","request_id":"req_011Cc2exjcNcL98vyw6dBjio"}
